article.headline: Whalen scores 21 for Gophers
article.story:
EVANSTON, Ill. -- Minnesota needed a late rally last year to
beat Northwestern after trailing big in the second half.

	   No comeback was necessary this time.

	   The No. 6 Golden Gophers (13-0, 2-0 Big Ten) hit their first
nine shots of the game and took a 25-2 lead on 3-pointers by
Shannon Schonrock and Lindsay Whalen to stay undefeated with a
72-40 win over the Wildcats on Thursday night.

	   Minnesota is one of just two unbeaten teams in the nation and is
off to its best start in school history. The Golden Gophers won 12
straight to open last season.

	   "We came out of the gates right away," Whalen said. "We got
it started on the defensive end. We got some steals and easy layups
and then we made our outside shots.

	   "That was kind of a nice cushion for us."

	   Was it ever.

	   Whalen hit a pair of free throws midway in the second half to
give Minnesota a 46-point lead, it largest of the game. She
finished 21 points and six assists, and Janel McCarville added 15
points.

	   The Golden Gophers didn't miss a shot until nearly six minutes
into the game, with the first errant attempt drawing derisive
applause from the crowd -- one of the few cheers of the night heard
from Wildcats fans.

	   That wasn't the case last season when Northwestern led by 18 at
halftime, only to have Minnesota rally for a three-point win.

	   Gophers coach Pam Borton reminded her team of last year's poor
start leading up to Thursday's game. It clearly left an impression.
The Golden Gophers shot 69 percent in the opening half.

	   "We talked about it a couple days ago," she said. "We also
talked about, no matter who we are playing, we have to come out and
play like a championship team. They have to have that focus no
matter who we're playing and where we are."

	   Whalen, third in the nation in scoring at 22.8 points a game,
was 6-for-9 from the field. The senior was one of four Gophers with
four steals as Northwestern (7-6, 0-2) committed 25 turnovers.

	   Alex Mueller's 3 for Northwestern made it 25-7, but Minnesota
went on another big run to increase its lead to 29 points midway
through the first half. McCarville stole the ball on consecutive
possessions and scored on easy layups for four of her nine points
during the 13-2 spurt.

	   The Gophers led 44-16 at halftime as Northwestern turned the
ball over on five of its first eight possessions.

	   Whalen's breakaway layup capped a 13-2 run for Minnesota to open
the second half for a 57-18 lead.

	   McCarville was 6-of-6 from the field as Minnesota shot 53
percent for the game, but just 28 percent in a sloppy second half.

	   Northwestern outscored Minnesota 16-2 over the final 8 minutes.

	   "Things came very, very easy the first half and the first five
minutes of the second half. We you have a 30- or 40-point lead I
think sometimes it's easy to let up," Borton said.

	   A.J. Glasauer and Michelle Zylstra had 11 points each to lead
Northwestern.

	   The Wildcats were missing four players, including leading scorer
Samantha McComb and starter Sara Kwasinski, due to injury or
illness.

	   "It throws off your rhythm, it throws off your psyche --
everything," coach June Olkowski said. "Especially if you're
playing the sixth-ranked team in the country."
